rComments: We covered a crazy volume of information (like 100 pages a week). Lectures were a bit dry but you can tell he wants students to do well. IMO lectures are optional IF you did all of his readings and take great notes. Fair marker if you follow rubric to a T- he also gives detailed feedback on papers which is appreciated.

By far the worst class I have taken thus far. He is a genuinely nice man, but his lack of enthusiasm, poorly constructed slides and vague responses to questions made this class unbearable. If I can recommend one thing for first year students, avoid him like the plague.

This guy couldnt lecture for the life of him. His lectures were something that to this day I cannot describe. His lectures were monotonous and not in a very clear order. The final exam was littered with spelling errors. Very reading intensive, because you dont learn anything from the lectures

I had him for HIS 1101. While I enjoy learning about history the only drawback for this class was that the lectures weren't really engaging. Prof Jesensky has a kind of monotone voice so I'd get bored at times during the lectures. Also, he doesn't post the slides so some mind find that tough. He's really specific with citation style for assignments

Going to class was a huge waste of time, he just went over the readings. The amount of reading was ridiculous (50+ pages per week). The final paper and essay topic proposal were graded unnecessarily harshly, and I lost a lot of marks for being 'too vague' when my topic and thesis were way more specific than the example given to us.
teacherRatingTags: ['Tough grader', 'Graded by few things', 'Get ready to read']

rComments: Avoid at all costs, particularly for POL courses. Course was listed as a seminar course but there was 0 class discussion, only lectures. Did not release rubrics until the day assignments were due. Elements on exams were not discussed in readings or in lectured. Term paper requirements were highly irregular and the marking scheme was absurd.
teacherRatingTags: ['Graded by few things', 'Tough grader', 'Get ready to read']

rComments: Do not take any classes with this prof if you can. The exam and midterm werent too difficult but the paper was excruciating to write and the criteria is extremely unclear and broad. Marcels lectures were so monotone and boring. He often had typos and wasnt clear. Dont take it if you can.
teacherRatingTags: ['Tough grader', 'Get ready to read', 'Graded by few things']

rComments: This prof gives you readings, his classes are entirely Power Point summaries of what you read during a given week. He does not teach or engage with students at all. As long as you do the readings and take good notes, you should be fine though. His lectures are useless. My only positive is that I found the readings actually very interesting.

Don't take this class if not mandatory! Very monotone Prof, no interaction with students during lectures, incoherent lectures, 50+ pages of readings a week, very harsh exams with loads of multiple choice, one essay question all super specific to things not even mentioned in class. Love history, this class made me question it.

Do NOT take a political science course with this professor. For a fourth year seminar-style geopolitics course, he made us do a 14 page research paper only worth 20%, as much as our proposal was worth. The exams were proctored and were unreasonably difficult. The professor was not clear on any of the grading schemes
He is extremely boring, does not answer questions from students, has no idea what he's doing, I would never take a class with him again. I wish I could drop this class.
teacherRatingTags: ['Graded by few things', 'Get ready to read']

rComments: Essentially his lectures are a review of the readings. However, if you havent done the readings you will not be able to make sense of what he is saying. He spits information but doesnt really explain. The textbook is essential for this class.
Makes absolutely no sense, prepare to red your textbook and figure it out from there. Good luck.
The readings were awful and the professor is very kind but hard to understand. The classes were so boring that eventually I stopped attending them.

don't take this class unless you have to. super dull, doesn't turn his camera on, one small assignment is worth as much as the exam, TAs are super harsh for a first year class. if you take his class, 100% get the textbook it will be your saving grace

If you have this teacher, run. He is honestly the worst teacher I have ever had. He does not share the PowerPoints so you have to create your own notes, uses the worst platform that works bad and no cam. He talks for 3 hours in the same tone, it is unbearable and he doesn't allow students to talk. Also, don't try to ask him a question he wont help

Get out if you still can. Horrible classes, lectures dry, dull and boring, this coming from a huge fan of history. The grading was some of the harshest I've ever experienced, an assignment is worth more than an exam etc. Ridiculous class, wouldn't recommend it under any circumstance.

J'ai bien aimé ce prof. Lors de l'examen de mi-session, j'ai paniqué parce qu'il y avait trop de questions sur l'examen et il a aidé à apaiser mon anxiété. Plus tard, il a décidé de ne pas compter certaines questions. Si tu lui parles en dehors des cours, il va bien t'aimer. Ce n'était pas difficile d'avoir une bonne note.

The online format didn't work well with him. Maybe he's better in person but online, he doesn't use Zoom, the first five or so lectures he never read the chat even though no one knew what was going on, his microphone is so quiet and he won't turn it up and what he's saying isn't at all engaging. Read the texts he gives and you'll be fine.
Where do I start? The exams? LONG for no reason. You're telling me I have to write over 2k words in an hour and a half? Lectures are awful. And TA grades really hard.

Prof. Jesenský was all right. It's clear that he's passionate about history, but it doesn't always translate to his lectures. The lectures are fast-paced and dry, so do the readings to understand the content (but go to the lectures to know what he emphasises). The exams are fair, but this class wasn't my favourite of the semester.
Very monotone lecturer but a fair grader and cares about how his students do in his class.

I'm not a history student, I took this class as an elective. The lectures are incredibly boring but he doesn't post them online so you need to go to class or you won't know anything. He takes attendance every day although he never explained how much we were allowed to miss. I bought the textbook but didn't use it once and still got an A-.

I really liked Professor Jessensky's lectures because you could tell that he was very knowledgable about the materials. If you skip his lectures you won't have proper notes and so it's important to go to class. He also takes attendence at every lecture. He's a great guy and a solid prof!
Really smart man . Super kind but OH MY GOD soooo boring.

One of the great profs at uOttawa. I'm not going to lie, his lectures are monotone and long. However, his is always there to help, he is very knowledgeable and super nice! As long as you go to class, take notes and do the lectures you'll get a great grade.
Horrible and very hard to understand. I will NEVER take another class with him.

The lectures themselves are dry as he is quite monotone but as long as you read the required text and show up to class to take notes he is a great professor! He is very easily approachable and would always take the time to clarify so that his students understood everything! Amazing class hands down!!

very boring. cant understand what hes saying. no motivation to listen because hes monotone, and it takes him like 3 hours to say one sentence. hes a really nice guy, and smart, but that doesnt mean hes good at teaching.

i found him to be dry and boring. he jumps back and forth from topics not staying with the order presented on his slides. he also has what appears to be a distinct lack of excitement for the subject; he stands in one place in the exact same position all class and stops in the middle of sentences.

Classes are structure very well (summarizes of previous lecture and the day's lecture). Powerpoint is used but he doesn't rely on them, so you have to make sure you listen to him. I tend to take notes from the lecture as opposed to the powerpoints, since he posts them on Virtual Campus. Always makes time for questions, but he speaks too quietly!

He's a lovely person and is very knowledgeable. Even though his teaching is quite dry, his lectures are very well structured (starts the class with a quick summary of the last class and ends with a summary of the class we just had) and he makes sure there is time for questions. Doesn't rely on his powerepoints too much so you have to listen.

His voice is a bit monotone, but he gets the subject across clearly.  Doesn't use virtual campus which is a bit annoying, but overall he does a good job.  Sometimes a bit difficult to understand because English is not his first language, but if you pay attention you should be fine.  Assignments are basic.

Dropped course after a couple weeks. Not my area to begin with. I'm sure the prof was nice, and seemed to know the material, but I couldn't really hear anything he said. Spoke very quietly, and periodically got this sort of "I just realized there are 200 people in front of me" look. To be fair, the room this class was taught in is just horrible.

He is clearly an expert on the topics, but he struggles during the lectures because english is not his first language.  Assignments are not difficult, but are very heavy, and you fail if you hand it in late.
